      "rationale": "Code verification completed using the FDA nozzle benchmark (ASME V&V 20). Normalized RMS error in velocity profiles is below 2% across all benchmark cases. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Grid convergence index (GCI) for hemolysis index must be below 5% on the fine-grid solution across all five operating points.",
      "rationale": "Three-level mesh refinement study performed (4.2 M, 9.8 M, 21.4 M cells). GCI for normalized index of hemolysis ranged from 1.8% to 4.3% across operating points, satisfying the 5% threshold. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental test conditions must match simulated boundary conditions within stated tolerances for flow rate (±5%), rotational speed (±1%), and fluid temperature (±2°C).",
      "rationale": "Bench tests conducted in a closed-loop circuit with calibrated Coriolis flow meter (±0.5%) and tachometer (±0.2%). Temperature maintained at 37 ± 0.8°C. All tolerances satisfied. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Predicted normalized index of hemolysis must agree with measured values within 15% at each of the five operating points, accounting for experimental uncertainty.",
      "rationale": "CFD-predicted NIH values compared against triplicate experimental measurements at each operating point. Maximum deviation was 11.4% at the highest shear-rate condition; all five points satisfy the 15% agreement criterion after uncertainty propagation. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The simulated quantity of interest (NIH) must be directly traceable to the regulatory acceptance criterion (RH < 1 relative to predicate).",
      "rationale": "NIH is the primary output mapped to the relative hemolysis index via established conversion. Traceability from CFD output to submission acceptance criterion is documented in the modeling plan. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation experiments must use the same pump geometry, fluid (bovine blood or validated analogue), and operating envelope as the COU.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on the identical FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry using fresh bovine blood within the CPB operating envelope (2–6 L/min, 2000–3500 RPM). Geometry, fluid, and boundary conditions are directly representative. Achieved level exceeds requirement."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Iterative convergence must be demonstrated by residual reduction of at least four orders of magnitude and stabilization of the hemolysis index monitor.",
      "rationale": "All simulations achieved residual reduction exceeding five orders of magnitude. NIH monitor values varied by less than 0.1% over the final 500 iterations, confirming iterative convergence. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Assessment of potential operator or analyst errors in model setup, boundary condition specification, and post-processing that could systematically bias hemolysis predictions.",
      "rationale": "The use error factor was not assessed on the grounds that the CFD workflow is fully automated via scripted batch submission and post-processing pipelines, and that analyst interaction is therefore considered negligible in this context. While this reasoning may have merit for certain error modes, it does not constitute a formal assessment of use error sources such as incorrect material property selection, turbulence model choice, or post-processing script errors, nor does it satisfy the criteria for scoping out or designating the factor not-applicable under ASME V&V 40. The factor therefore remains not-assessed."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "The hemolysis power-law model form (Giersiepen-Wurzinger) must be justified against alternative formulations and its applicability to the shear-exposure range in the COU demonstrated.",
      "rationale": "Sensitivity analysis comparing Giersiepen-Wurzinger, Heuser-Optiz, and Zhang power-law models performed across all five operating points. Maximum inter-model NIH spread was 8.2%, within acceptable bounds for comparative assessment. Model form selection documented and justified. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Key model inputs (blood viscosity, density, power-law exponents, boundary flow rates) must be characterized with uncertainty bounds and their influence on NIH quantified via sensitivity analysis.",
      "rationale": "One-at-a-time sensitivity analysis performed for all eight primary model inputs. Blood viscosity (non-Newtonian Carreau parameters) and power-law exponent alpha identified as dominant contributors. Monte Carlo propagation (n=500) yields NIH 95th-percentile uncertainty of ±12%, within accepted bounds for MRL 3. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Experimental blood samples must be characterized for hematocrit, plasma hemoglobin baseline, and storage age; samples outside specification must be excluded.",
      "rationale": "All blood samples drawn within 24 hours of use; hematocrit maintained at 33 ± 2%; baseline plasma hemoglobin confirmed below 20 mg/dL prior to each test. Two samples excluded for elevated baseline; replacement samples obtained. Required level met."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "CFD boundary conditions must be demonstrated to be equivalent to experimental conditions, with documented mapping of measured quantities to simulation inputs.",
      "rationale": "Time-averaged inlet velocity profiles from PIV measurements used directly as CFD inlet boundary conditions. Outlet pressure boundary conditions set to match measured system resistance curve. Equivalency mapping table provided in the V&V report appendix. Required level met."
    }
